# 65_units_parser_smoke — substrate parser regression suite (s263 m7).
#
# Validates the math-expression parser plumbing in
# UnitSystem::parse_expr — the same engine that runs when a user types
# into ANY substrate SpinButton or CurvzSpinButton. This smoke
# addresses the substrate widget `ins_can_pw` (Pixel-mode canvas
# width spinner in the inspector); same widget smoke 21 already
# uses, exercised through a different verb here.
#
# ── Why this smoke exists ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# s263 m4 added `"` as an inch suffix to the length-domain parser
# (print-design muscle memory; blueprints write `5"`); s263 m5
# replaced the parser's binary allow_units flag with a Domain enum
# (Length / Angle / Percentage / Dimensionless), per-domain legal
# unit sets, structural cross-domain refusal. The Domain-aware path
# is reachable through CurvzSpinButton instances (rotation fields,
# inspector geometry fields with units), but the s187 design fork is
# still open — CurvzSpinButton inherits from Gtk::SpinButton
# directly, NOT from the substrate widget, so the Domain-aware
# parser isn't script-addressable today.
#
# What IS addressable today is the substrate widget's parser, which
# routes through the legacy `allow_units=false` compat path that
# m5's wrapper maps to Domain::Dimensionless. So this smoke validates
# the dimensionless-substrate parser path: math, parens, precedence,
# unary minus, and refusals (no suffixes legal in Dimensionless).
#
# That's still real coverage. The m5 work touched this code path —
# the compat wrapper is what makes the substrate's existing parser
# behaviour survive the Domain enum migration. A regression here
# would fail a smoke; same convergent-evidence shape s225-style
# substrate smokes use.
#
# Once the s187 design fork resolves (CurvzSpinButton becomes a
# substrate widget), this smoke gains a companion `66_units_domain_
# smoke` that exercises Length / Angle / Percentage domains on the
# rich widgets, with per-domain suffix asserts and cross-domain
# refusal asserts.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Two verb surfaces on `ins_can_pw`:
#
#   set <number>     — direct numeric back-door; bypasses parser.
#                      Used to establish a known initial state for
#                      refusal asserts (value-didn't-change is the
#                      assertion).
#   parse <string>   — runs the string through the parser; commits
#                      on success (signal_value_changed fires inline),
#                      no-op on refusal. Verb's Bool return is
#                      operator-visual on the trace echo; the smoke
#                      asserts on the post-call value query, NOT on
#                      the parse return (DSL assert is equality-only
#                      on query results — same constraint smoke 44 and
#                      smoke 63 both work around).
#                      s263 m6 added this verb to the substrate
#                      widget; smoke 65 is its first regression
#                      consumer.
#
# One query surface:
#
#   value            — Double; reads the current adjustment value.
#                      The smoke's invariant for every parse case:
#                      after a happy-path parse, value commits to the
#                      expected scalar; after a refusal-path parse,
#                      value is unchanged from its pre-parse state.
#
# Coverage shape (FOUR-PHASE per the s236+ smoke discipline):
#
#   BUILD UP   : Phase 1 establishes a known starting value via the
#                set back-door (256, a portable canvas-width default).
#   VALIDATE   : Phase 2 exercises happy-path parses (math, parens,
#                precedence, subtraction). Each asserts the
#                post-parse value matches the expected scalar.
#   FIND EDGES : Phase 3 exercises refusals (out-of-range, division
#                by zero, malformed). Each asserts the post-parse
#                value stayed at 256.
#   FIND EDGES : Phase 4 exercises domain refusals (Length suffixes,
#                Angle suffixes — all illegal in Dimensionless). Same
#                pattern: value unchanged at 256.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# ScripterWindow listener, RunContext::Scripter. Substrate widget
# verbs are not RunContext-gated (substrate is below the gating
# layer — it's plumbing every higher Scriptable rides on); the parse
# verb is therefore callable from every context including Macro,
# matching the pattern smoke 21 and others rely on.
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# The smoke writes to ins_can_pw. The Pixel-mode width is a real
# document property — committing 256 at the end IS a state change
# Scott will observe in the inspector. Smoke 21 already uses this
# widget with the same end-state convention; following it here keeps
# the inspector predictable across smokes. If Scott's current document
# has a different launch width, the Phase 1 `set 256` normalizes it
# for the smoke duration.
#
# ── Predicted observables ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected summary line at smoke close:
#
#   25 lines, 12 pass, 0 fail, 0 error
#
# Trace breakdown:
#   Phase 1 (init):           1 set + 1 assert       = 2 lines, 1 pass
#   Phase 2 (5 happy paths):  5 parse + 5 assert    = 10 lines, 5 pass
#   Phase 3 (1 reset + 4 refusals):
#                             1 set + 4 (parse+assert)
#                                                    = 9 lines, 4 pass
#   Phase 4 (2 domain refusals; inch-quote skipped — see Phase 4
#            block for the DSL-escape gap explanation):
#                             2 (parse+assert)       = 4 lines, 2 pass
#   TOTAL:                                            25 lines, 12 pass
#
# v1 → v2 fix-re-ship notes:
#   - Phase 2 decimal test: 256.5 → 256.4 to avoid C++ std::round
#     half-away-from-zero ambiguity (256.5 rounds UP to 257, not
#     down to 256 — v1 prediction was wrong about the direction).
#   - Phase 4 inch-quote test: removed; the DSL tokenizer has no
#     string-escape mechanism, so `parse "5\""` can't reach the
#     parser as a single string arg. Inch-quote coverage stays in
#     the GUI text-entry path (manual smoke); the script-side gap
#     is banked as a backlog item.
#
# If any assertion fails, the parser has regressed against the m4-m5
# spec. If a parse throws an uncaught exception instead of returning
# false, the error count goes up — separate failure mode from a fail.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP — establish known starting value ===

#[sub] Direct numeric set bypassing the parser; gives Phase 3 / 4
#[sub] refusal cases a known value to assert "didn't change" against.

ins_can_pw set 256.0
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE — happy-path parses ===

#[sub] Plain integer math. The `parse` verb commits the value and
#[sub] returns true (operator-visual on the trace's echo line);
#[sub] the equality assert is on the post-commit value query.

ins_can_pw parse "100"
assert ins_can_pw value == 100.0

#[sub] Decimal math. ins_can_pw has digits=0 so 256.4 rounds to 256
#[sub] on commit (std::round, half-away-from-zero — 256.5 would round
#[sub] UP to 257 per C++ standard, so the smoke uses 256.4 to test
#[sub] rounding without straddling the half-way ambiguity). This is
#[sub] the substrate widget's integer-style spin behaviour, documented
#[sub] in signal_input — get_digits()==0 triggers round in
#[sub] try_parse_and_commit (same as in signal_input's pre-existing
#[sub] path).

ins_can_pw parse "256.4"
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] Arithmetic with operator precedence — multiplication binds
#[sub] tighter than addition. 5 + 3 * 2 should commit as 11, not 16.

ins_can_pw parse "5 + 3 * 2"
assert ins_can_pw value == 11.0

#[sub] Parentheses override precedence — (5 + 3) * 2 should commit
#[sub] as 16. Exercises the parser's primary() recursive-descent
#[sub] paren branch.

ins_can_pw parse "(5 + 3) * 2"
assert ins_can_pw value == 16.0

#[sub] Subtraction. 100 - 50 should commit as 50. ins_can_pw's lower
#[sub] bound is 1, so the result is in range.

ins_can_pw parse "100 - 50"
assert ins_can_pw value == 50.0

#[sub] === Phase 3: FIND EDGES — structural refusals ===

#[sub] Re-establish a known pre-refusal value so refusal asserts can
#[sub] check "value didn't change." The smoke's refusal-class
#[sub] invariant: parse returns false (operator-visual on echo),
#[sub] value query stays at 256.

ins_can_pw set 256.0

#[sub] Out-of-range value — below the adjustment's lower bound (1).
#[sub] Parser parses cleanly but the range clamp in
#[sub] try_parse_and_commit refuses. Value unchanged.

ins_can_pw parse "0"
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] Division by zero — parser's term() throws "Division by zero."
#[sub] try_parse_and_commit catches and returns false. Value unchanged.

ins_can_pw parse "1 / 0"
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] Malformed expression — trailing operator. Parser sees no
#[sub] operand after `+`; throws "Missing value." or similar.
#[sub] try_parse_and_commit catches and returns false. Value unchanged.

ins_can_pw parse "5 + "
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] Unclosed parenthesis — parser throws "Unclosed parenthesis."
#[sub] try_parse_and_commit catches and returns false. Value unchanged.

ins_can_pw parse "(5 + 3"
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] === Phase 4: FIND EDGES — domain refusals ===

#[sub] The substrate widget is dimensionless: NO suffixes legal.
#[sub] Every domain's suffix-set is illegal here. The compat wrapper
#[sub] (s263 m5) routes allow_units=false through Domain::Dimensionless
#[sub] which throws "Units not allowed here" on any letter run or
#[sub] non-dimensionless symbol.

#[sub] Length letter suffix. `5in` should refuse with "Units not
#[sub] allowed here: 'in'." Value unchanged at 256.

ins_can_pw parse "5in"
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] Inch quote (s263 m4 added `"` to Length domain) is NOT
#[sub] tested through this smoke. The DSL tokenizer in
#[sub] ScriptListener::tokenise has no string-escape mechanism —
#[sub] `\"` is two characters (backslash + quote), the quote ends
#[sub] the string, and the backslash gets eaten into the previous
#[sub] token. So `parse "5\""` mis-tokenizes; the `parse` verb sees
#[sub] either zero or two args and throws "expects one string arg".
#[sub] The inch-quote behaviour IS exercised through the GUI text
#[sub] entry (typing `5"` into a length-domain CurvzSpinButton),
#[sub] which is its dominant use case anyway. Banked as a backlog
#[sub] item: if more script-string-with-quote cases appear in the
#[sub] corpus, escape handling becomes worth adding to the
#[sub] tokenizer; until then, GUI-only coverage is the honest
#[sub] answer.

#[sub] Angle letter suffix. `45deg` refuses with "Units not allowed
#[sub] here: 'deg'." in dimensionless context. Value unchanged.

ins_can_pw parse "45deg"
assert ins_can_pw value == 256.0

#[sub] === Predicted observables ────────────────────────────────────────────

#[sub] Expected summary line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   25 lines, 12 pass, 0 fail, 0 error
#[sub]
#[sub] All assertions are equality-form on Double (value query) per
#[sub] the DSL's equality-only-on-query rule. The smoke is
#[sub] structurally a regression net for the m4-m5 parser work; no
#[sub] smoke-level invariant holds without all 12 PASSes.
#[sub]
#[sub] Companion smoke 66 (banked for when s187 design fork
#[sub] resolves): exercises the Domain-aware parser via
#[sub] CurvzSpinButton instances once they become substrate-
#[sub] addressable. Length / Angle / Percentage happy paths;
#[sub] cross-domain refusals (5\" + 30deg, etc.); same shape as
#[sub] this smoke with the Dimensionless restriction removed.
